  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Xerosis (dry skin) is the most common cause of pruritus in the elderly. The dominant symptom is generalized itching that is usually worse in the winter (low humidity). Frequent bathing and use of soap, detergents, and alcohol-containing skin products worsen xerosis. Management consists of increasing ambient humidity; decreasing the frequency of bathing; using lukewarm water and mild skin cleansers; avoiding drying skin products (e.g., alcohol-based) and irritating clothing; and liberal and frequent use of emollients. Emollients should be applied immediately after bathing to enhance hydration. First-generation antihistamines (e.g., hydroxyzine, diphenhydramine) can be helpful, particularly if taken at bedtime.",
