  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Polycythemia vera is characterized by increased red cell mass, often accompanied by leukocytosis and thrombocytosis. Common presenting symptoms include headache, dizziness, visual disturbances, pruritus, and erythromelalgia. Pruritus, especially after a warm bath or shower (aquagenic pruritus), occurs in 40% of patients with polycythemia vera and may be the presenting symptom. It is thought to be due to histamine and other mediators released from basophils or mast cells with increased histamine content in this disorder. Physical examination usually reveals plethora, splenomegaly, and occasionally hepatomegaly. Diagnosis requires elevated hemoglobin (>16.5 g/dL in men, >16.0 g/dL in women) or hematocrit (>49% in men, >48% in women) and JAK2 mutation (found in >95% of cases).",
