  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Hyperthyroidism is associated with pruritus in 4-11% of patients. The increased metabolic rate leads to vasodilation and heat intolerance, which can exacerbate pruritus. Thyroid hormones can also increase IgE-mediated mast cell degranulation, contributing to pruritus. Common manifestations of hyperthyroidism include weight loss despite increased appetite, heat intolerance, sweating, palpitations, anxiety, tremor, and tachycardia. Physical examination may reveal goiter, exophthalmos (in Graves' disease), and hyperreflexia. The diagnosis is confirmed by suppressed TSH and elevated free T4 levels.",
